The research of the principal investigator (PI) is motivated by the classical notion of Symmetry. It is well-known that the symmetries of objects we can see, classical objects, form a group. Yet symmetries of (unobserved) quantum objects, or rather, of their noncommutative algebras of functions, are of interest here. Such quantum algebras are rigid in the classical sense as they admit few group actions in general. This can be rectified by expanding to actions of Hopf algebras, which indeed forms a solid foundation for the study of Quantum Symmetry. The PI's main objective was to push this theory further. The existence of Genuine Quantum Symmetry (e.g. Hopf actions that do not factor through group actions) will be examined and the PI further developed the invariant theory and the study of other objects that arise from such symmetries. Moreover, the PI examined Quantum Symmetry in the framework of tensor categories, which, to the end of capturing all symmetries of quantum objects, goes beyond actions of Hopf algebras.


Some findings included: 

(1) the production examples of "weak quantum symmetries" by constructing a monoidal functor from a certain corepresentation category of a bialgebra L to the corepresentation category of a weak bialgebra built from L (a "quantum transformation groupoid"); 

(2) the construction of braided commutative algebras in braided monoidal categories by generalizing Davydov's full center construction of commutative algebras in centers of monoidal categories, such categories include representations of important Hopf algebras (quantum groups); 

(3) an introduction of methods for classifying actions of finite-dimensional Hopf algebras on path algebras of quivers and more generally on tensor algebras over semisimple algebras, within the broader framework of finite (multi-)tensor categories; 

(4) the computation of the Gelfand-Kirillov dimension of cosemisimple Hopf algebras that arise as deformations of a linearly reductive algebraic group, generalizing results of Goodearl-Zhang (2007), of Banica-Vergnioux (2009), and of D'Andrea-Pinzari-Rossi (2017).





